      "note": "The chapter's rhetorical architecture is that of an ancient Near Eastern covenant lawsuit (rib): (1) summons (23:1-2), (2) historical review of the relationship and its violation (23:3-21), (3) indictment (23:22-35), (4) formal arraignment before a judge (23:36-45), (5) sentence of execution (23:46-48), (6) declaration of purpose (23:49). The 'therefore' pivots mark the transitions between phases. Ezekiel is not writing poetry; he is conducting a legal proceeding in prophetic form."
